(3, 'Shneidermans Eight Golden Rules', 'Shneidermans Eight Golden rules blogpost ', 'Summary:\r\n\r\nI think Shneiderman\'s 8 principals are smart and are needed in basics of interface design. \r\n\r\nHis first Principal is Consistency which I think is key in interface design as if it was inconsistent, users will get more frustrated from using it , while if there is consistency the users are going to find the experience easier. Although an argument could be made that it can\'t be too consistent as users would like to see variation in use of icons, colours etc. everything looking the same will make the users feel bored of even looking at the interface and will be less inclined to use it so I feel Shneiderman is right but too much consistency isn\'t a good principal as it would feel boring and users may not be inclined to use new interfaces if they\'re a lack of changes.   \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThis example shows that Apples MAC OS has used a consistent menu bar from the 1980s until modern day , Macs menu bar is very popular and a nice feature to the MAC OS , new users can adapt to it quickly and experienced users know what the menu bar is so it\'s easier to adapt to the new OS\r\n\r\n\r\nI do agree with Shneiderman\'s principal on shortcuts as they help do tasks easier and more time efficient for the user  I feel that shortcuts must be simple and should be no more than 2 keys like CTRL + C for copy CTRL + V for paste as the user gets more experienced to shortcuts they are more likely to use them and it will be a much nicer user experience. \r\n\r\n\r\nI think a flaw of the shortcuts could be they are many to learn and some may feel a bit confusing and not really relevant to the keys that need typing for example CTRL + D is a weird one to bookmark a website I would of guessed it would be CTRL + B. Overall Though I believe keyboard shortcuts are a decent feature in interfaces.  \r\n\r\n\r\nHis 3rd Principal is that users must be offered informative feedback which I think is a good idea, too many times in computers like windows an error message will come up with an error code which is annoying for users to receive as it doesn’t tell them what is entirely going on and mike make the user very frustrated and annoyed and inclined to use other software. \r\n\r\nThis is a bad example of the 3rd principal as it just looks very confusing to the average computer user . As a good designer error messages should be human-readable.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe 4th Principal is similar to the 3rd as the interface should be communicating with the user and actions should be said what they lead to. For example if a user is buying something online a message should say \'Thank You your purchase has been completed!\' and a proof of a receipt. I believe that this principal shouldn\'t be argue against it is really a must to have even if they needs to be more coding \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nShneiderman\'s 5th principal was to offer users simple error handling by having step by step instructions to fix for example a simple user \r\n\r\n\r\nAs shown here the user is notified where they went wrong in the register process. \r\nBut as Shneiderman thinks that the user should receive step by step instructions to solve certain issues but this is Harder and less time efficient to code so they\'re points on both arguments whether this principal is valid. Overall though I believe users should be offered simple error handling.\r\n\r\nHis 6th Principal is To permit easy reversal of actions as he believes \" This feature relieves anxiety, since the user knows the errors can be un-done; it thus encourages exploration of unfamiliar options\" His 6th principal is widely and commonly used in any Microsoft product for example the undo and redo buttons are in nearly every one of them.    \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThe 7th Principal is to support internal locus of control which is allowing users to be the initiators of actions. Which gives the user the sense they are in full control of events occurring in their digital space.\r\n\r\nThis above is allowing the user to force Quit/ close the program. An flaw of the principal could be with that much power users may be doing too much which could lead to mistakes and system could break and falter because the user wasn\'t knowing what they are doing. Although I do like the principal as it is the user\'s computer after all. \r\n\r\n\r\nThe last principal of Shneidermans was the reduce short term memory load, Human attention is limited and humans can only focus on 5 items in our short term memory so Shneiderman thinks that interfaces need to be simplified so it is easier on users minds and not to be too complicated as users are less likely to use interfaces which are much more complicated. The iPhones home screen has 4 app icons to sit at the bottom of the screen this is based on Shneiderman\'s principal. \r\n\r\n\r\n On the other hand People may think that a simplified interface is basic and poor to look at and would rather use a better more advanced interface , I believe that interfaces should be simplified especially for new users as a complicated interface could be overwhelming for new users but it can\'t be too basic as it will attract less people to use the interface. \r\n\r\n\r\nOverall, I think Shneiderman\'s principals should be considered as he has very good points on building a successful interface maybe not everything he says should be implemented but he mentions the basics which I believe should be used in all interfaces or at least be considered to be implemented.    \r\n', 0x696d616765732f363734656534303062613732382e6a7067, '2024-12-03'),
(4, 'Morville\'s Honeycomb of UX', 'A Blogpost on Morville\'s Honeycomb of UX ', 'Peter Morville is a designer and information architect and has been working in the field since 1994. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFrom &lt;https://whiteboard.office.com/me/whiteboards/p/c3BvOmh0dHBzOi8vZ2lnLW15LnNoYXJlcG9pbnQuY29tL3BlcnNvbmFsL2NvcmtldHRhX2Vhc3RyaWRpbmdjb2xsZWdlX2FjX3Vr/b!m3Ex9jnh20SgDsSI8dT8xNkG0bGGsrFFnthXmyVneIEcb6mTfeW_RLSSqwZbdu3D/01KS7OP6PNL5DCWIBLK5BJO6C46QMDC35X&gt; \r\n\r\nThe diagram above shows that Morville believed they had to be a balance between the 3 for a good User Experience (UX) design.\r\n\r\nMorville also created the famous Honeycomb design  it is used as a tool which explains the various facets of user experience design,  Morville believed all of these was required in UX designs.\r\n	\r\n\r\nEach facet of user experience can be defined by the diagram above. \r\n\r\nUsability / Useable - Morville believed that the system has to be design in a familiar way for the user to be able to understate simply so the user learning curve is as small as possible.\r\n\r\n\r\nUseful-  If the user does not need a feature then there is no real purpose of having the feature in your website, he believes that all features in website should be useable and have a good purpose \r\n\r\n\r\nDesirable- the aesthetic of the product must be simple and to the point and easy to translate, Morville believed that UX shouldn&#039;t be overcomplicated then what it needs to be the website must have simple features for people who are confused in accessing the source. \r\n \r\nFindable- The information need to be easy to find for the user in which information they may require; users should be able to navigate in a way which makes sense if there is a problem it should be easy to find a solution.\r\n\r\nAccessible- Product should be designed for users with disabilities so they can have the same user experience as others , View my other blogpost on Accessibility Principles \r\n\r\nCredible- The company and the product must be trusted \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n', 0x696d616765732f363735383361383932353431332e706e67, '2024-12-03'),
