(20, 'Comparing Tools I Used in Software Development', 'A post on how I used different software and tools for software/website development', 'During the process of creating the website I used different software to write and analyse code for my project\r\n\r\nFor me Dreamweaver has some good features like \r\n Live View editing: Dreamweaver offers a convenient feature where you can directly edit text and image attributes and add classes in the Live View. \r\nAlthough, in vs code live editing and preview will have to be done by enabling certain extensions. \r\nDreamweaver can also directly go to a server without using xammp although xampp could still be used if preferred.  \r\n\r\nVS Code although requires software like xampp to run the live server (localhost) of the website. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFor a paid software I think dreamweaver has more advanced features and for experienced coders who are willing to spend money on it and wanted something from vs code I would recommend but for new coders I would recommend vs code, Vs code is simple and many extensions can be added if need and other programming languages can be accessed , vs code really isn&rsquo;t overwhelming which I think dreamweaver is , I used vs code as a new coder for my website\r\nAnother positive feature of vs code is the access to git hub where you can push files to your account\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nWe used many other tools Firstly Figma is a very useful tool  for creating design for my website , it is an web application , Its a free software which is very useful in my opinion to creating a design for an application or an website. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThe main bar has , an option to create a frame you will have the option if it&#039;s for a phone or a desktop , you can create many shapes by the square option , \r\n\r\nYou can also add text in there and comments if you wanted to leave notes on what you&#039;re doing or someone giving feedback. I liked this feature as when  other people was looking at my design they was able to leave a comment to show what I could do to improve. \r\n\r\nThere is also a developer mode when your finished with the design by ticking the box \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n\r\nThis bar shows the pointer , a ruler if you want to measure the distance between the pixels and a comment button. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThe sidebar is helpful for when you are coding as it gives you some basic code in CSS like the background hexadecimal \r\n\r\nI used Figma to create designs like this:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nI would say the designs look professional.\r\nOverall Figma was very useful for creating designs for my website and helped me as I was developing with my website , overall it isn&#039;t a perfect app\r\nBut I think its great for designing website or software. \r\n\r\n\r\nAnother tool I used was Miro this is a website which is almost used as a whiteboard to draft up ideas, it was useful for planning my structure for my blogsite\r\n\r\nLike how we can view posts and write a post and how this is validated, in other projects for more complex websites I have gone in depth for \r\nOur group project \r\n\r\nUsing Miro you can create a mind map very easily , a very useful feature for me was that Miro has an preset board available\r\n\r\n They&#039;re options for a flowchart , mind map and many more options for creating a board , it helped me with ideas and makes it more efficient then creating a completely blank board\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThe sidebar has every thing you need in Miro You can create a sticky note, \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nAdding text , which is customisable like different fonts and colour e.t.c\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThey&#039;re many shapes which can be added to the whiteboard which helps suits whatever the user needs by having multiple customisation.  \r\n\r\n\r\nOverall I believe Miro is a great option for planning in website development due to its versatility, functionality and customisation it would\r\nDefinitely be on of my favourite resources in projects due to the reasons listed above , it&#039;s very similar to Microsoft Whiteboard but I feel this just edges it. \r\n\r\n\r\nMicrosoft Teams is a very useful tool when it comes to software development. Microsoft Teams is an application where you collaborate ideas\r\nAnd work in a group. Teams is used as a professional business source in modern day but Teams can be used for multiple things , mainly I use\r\nTeams for collaboration with my course friends. We have a group chat in projects which is professional and verstalie , rather then communicating in person\r\nTeams can be acsessed from anywhere (requiring internet) For software developers working in a team Microsoft Teams is a great option . \r\nA big feature is the acsess to files and sharing them \r\n\r\nTeams has an assignment page should any assignments need completing , we can upload our files to the assignment and then they will be able \r\nTo be accessed from multiple devices , showing the versatility and why teams is such a popular choice. \r\n\r\nWe have multiple channels ready to be accessed  for certain sections we need to discuss they can be hidden if the user decides they don&rsquo;t\r\nWant to see other sections , this helps keep different work and files separate and easy for users to be able to understand which section is which.\r\n\r\nFor example teams almost has its own file explorer inside , multiple folders can be created and files can be uploaded (if you have acsess to do so).\r\n\r\nTeams has access to a class notebook (OneNote) which has been key for software development (will talk about later).\r\n\r\nTeams also has a chats section where you can create a private message or a group chat by adding people to it , I found teams group chats \r\nTo be a great option for when you need some help or collaborating \r\n\r\n\r\nThis an example of our chats which help us with the group project and make sure we are focused and assigned a task.\r\nTeams also has the option to have a virtual meeting where it&rsquo;s a call , this can also help collaboration and doing work remotely. \r\n\r\n\r\nOverall Teams is such a good tool if you are in a group of developers due to its functionality, purpose and professionalism  teams is a great resource \r\nWhich is a MUST use. \r\n\r\n\r\nXampp is a software that I used for hosting a live server \r\n\r\n\r\nXampp is great for a local server and testing to see what your website looks like on a web browser \r\nApache is the server which allows the content like HTML to be accessed on the web browser, MySQL is the database\r\nFor the website you are testing , these two are the only Modules I use of Xampp and they are very useful for testing a live website. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nWhen you type in Localhost  on your web browser a home page will come up , the top right is phpMyadmin this is a local database\r\n for your website and can be linked by writing SQL \r\n\r\nThey&#039;re many good functions on phpMyAdmin  where you can import a database , create a database and export it , you can create tables which can store data\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nphpMyadmin has tables inside where  you can create sections like an id title , this will be coded by SQL. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nApache gets the opportunity to see your HTML and CSS in a browser like its on a real server!\r\n\r\n\r\nOverall Xampp is very useful tool for hosting a private local server due to its functionality, ease and multiple features it \r\nIs a top choice for a live server. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nMicrosoft Planner is a very useful tool for planning on software development. The example above is from our group project creating a website\r\nWe can create multiple tickets and assign people who are doing this the prioirty add attachments to the tickets and when they need to be completed by\r\nFor me Planner is a very good planner and a useful source for my project work. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThis is an example of the ticket we can also checklists to make it a step by step process , planner is linked with teams as mentioned before \r\nAs You can invite the team to view the group / personal planner , there is also a comment section if any comments are needed. \r\n\r\nOverall Project Planner is a great resource for group work and personal work as it&rsquo;s a digital planner which can help organise you and fr software development\r\nIts a very useful tool.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe last useful tool I used for my website is OneNote this was a big part of my project for documenting progress. \r\n\r\n \r\nOneNote is like word but inside of teams, You can create tables write text e.t.c It helped me a lot keep notes and finalise evidence\r\nFor my project I kept my test Log in OneNote \r\n\r\nIt was a great resource for notes and it is very versatile like the other software where I can acsess it at home or on any other devices.\r\n\r\nOverall OneNote is a great resource for documenting things like test logs while on software development I found it really useful. \r\n\r\nOverall VS Code is the best Tool as it was the tool I used the most to build my code , I think the layout and self -built in functions made this a really good tool\r\n\r\n', 0x696d616765732f363737643139653162346665662e706e67, '2024-12-28'),
(21, 'A Comparison of Programming Languages and their Uses', 'A post for project 2 on Programming languages and their uses. ', 'Throughout our course so far we have studied many programming languages which have been PHP, HTML, CSS, Python C# and a little bit of JavaScript although they are all high level programming languages they all have a different purpose and uses for example what language do use you use for web development , what to do for making games? So I will discuss the different uses of each language.\r\n\r\nFor project 1 we was tasked to create a blogsite for the languages we had to use HTML and CSS for the &quot;front end&quot; of the website. &quot;Front end &quot; is what the website looks like, how it is designed and layed out for the users experience and how they interact with the website. \r\n\r\nHypertext Markup Language is the standard well used markup language used for documents designed to be in a web browser. As I&#039;ve mentioned before it defines the content and structure of the website. its initial release was in 1992 \r\nWeb browsers receive HTML documents from a web server or from local storage and render the documents into multimedia web pages. HTML is a language which uses different syntax from others , HTML elements are delineated by tags, written using angle brackets like this &lt;&gt;. \r\nHTML can embed programming languages in their code, which is mostly JavaScript but I will talk later on about the programming languages we used in our websites. \r\n\r\nCascading Style Sheets (CSS) is a way to add design or style to a website without CSS the websites you look at daily would just be text with no design or placement, CSS is what makes websites look attractive to users, it is written in a markup language such as HTML. CSS is designed to enable the separation of content and presentation, including layout, colours, and fonts. This separation can improve content accessibility, since the content can be written without concern for its presentation; provide more flexibility and control in the specification of presentation characteristics. \r\n\r\nPHP is a general-purpose scripting language geared towards web development.t was originally created by Danish-Canadian programmer Rasmus Lerdorf in 1993 and released in 1995. As PHP is scripting/programming language if used alongside HTML PHP  is not code which defies what you see in a web page it&#039;s what happens &quot;behind the scene&quot; for more complex websites a language like PHP must be used as it is the process of what happens, as HTML and CS is for &quot;front-end&quot; developers PHP is more &quot;back-end&quot; When you register an account for example HTML will create the form for this but PHP will gather the data and coders will typically use PHP to send information to a database. Most websites need PHP to function as HTML is limited in this sense. \r\n\r\nJavaScript, often abbreviated as JS, is a programming language and core technology of the Web, alongside HTML and CSS. 99% of websites use JavaScript on the client side for webpage behaviour.\r\nJavaScript is focused on what the user is doing in the website and how they are interacting with it responses are typically programmed in JavaScript. \r\nit first appeared in 1995.\r\n\r\nSo for my project 1 blogsite I used HTML for the structure and content of the website, CSS for the design a little bit of JavaScript (less then I should) and PHP for the process and connection to the database (PHPMyadmin). \r\n\r\n\r\nFor project 3 I will be using C# as a programming language used with the unity engine to create an immersive experience\r\n\r\nC# is a high-level programming language developed by Microsoft that runs on the .NET, C# is used to develop web apps,desktop apps, mobile apps, games and much more. \r\n\r\nPython (which we haven&#039;t used yet) is a high level popular programming language written similarly to C# , Python first appeared in 1991. Python is commonly sued for developing websites ( an alternative to PHP) and software, task automation , data analysis, and data visualisation. Python is a very popular language but we are yet to use it in any project so far.    \r\n', 0x696d616765732f363737626266306132626263632e706e67, '2025-01-05'),
(29, 'Useful Sources for Skills Development in Software and Interactive Media', 'A blogpost on Useful sources for software development ', 'I used multiple sources in software development I will evaluate which one was the least useful and which was useful , which wasn\'t and  which sources I will be using again.\r\n\r\nFor creating my website , it was going to be tough as it was my first experience creating one so my tutor directed me to use an app called Mimo.\r\n\r\nMimo is an application which contains courses simple and extensive to help new programmers learn more about the code, I took the Full stack developer option and nearly completed the Into to Web Development section. Mimo was very useful for helping understanding the basics and structure of HTML , it helped me understand key elements and functions in HTML. \r\nMimo helped me a bit and is a great source for software development, they have free courses for other programming languages like Python, JavaScript and SQL. Although they\'re negatives of the software. One thing is the heart system, it is very annoying that if you make so many mistakes that you are timed out, and you have to pay for an subscription to have unlimited hearts, but overall if you are a beginner I would recommend Mimo as a source. \r\n\r\nYouTube is a useful source for software development, YouTube is a social media and online video sharing platform. I watched specific accounts and videos to help understand concepts of programming. For PHP I watched this video which contained many other mini videos of PHP functions but combined into one 2 hour video , this was really helpful in understanding PHP and is a great resource for understanding the basics and testing them so you can use them in future projects. PHP Full Course for non-haters 🐘 \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThe PHP Courses on YouTube from a YouTuber called Bro Code.\r\nLink to their YouTube profile: https://www.youtube.com/@BroCodez   \r\nBro code has videos on other programming languages as well, Python , C# , C++, JavaScript, HTML and CSS where they have videos on. All of his videos are free to view which is a great source if you don&#039;t want to spend money, considering he has over 2 million subscribers , Bro code is very popular and for a reason he is definitely one of the best in the whole platform for learning coding. A slight con is that he doesn\'t cover every feature in the language but he covers 90% of it I would say for a free resource I think its top notch and it is a very useful source (YouTube) for software development watching Bro Codes videos it definitely made me more confident.          \r\n\r\nW3 schools was a resource I used during the coding and was probably the best. W3 Schools has nearly every programming language there is , they have guides for HTML,CSS, JavaScript, SQL ,Python, PHP, C++ , C# , MYSQL and many more. Every language they have on there has simple and easy tutorials to follow, they all so have pages to test their scripts and see what it does this is a great feature of w3 schools website. They have simple tutorials for people first coding and as you scroll down the side the features they describe is much more advanced. For HTML every single Tag has its own page with a definition and usage , the in-depthness of this websites outstands me especially for a free resource in python as well every function has its own definition and usage which is very helpful for new programmers looking to understand what it does. \r\nI would say this is the best resource there is for software development hands down due to it having everything you need basically and it is free! Maybe on tweak would be to add videos to their explanations. \r\n\r\nAnother source  I used to help my debug issues with claude.ai , I didn\'t use it to develop my code but to understand the errors I made , sometimes syntax or logic so I would say it\'s a very useful resource for that. \r\nClaude.ai is \r\nlaude AI (Claude) is a generative artificial intelligent  chatbot developed by the research firm Anthropic it can help build programming code. It\'s a much better resource then chat gpt as it explains the code much better it provides in depth analysis to what you can do to fix the code and improve it. One fetch is that sometimes they over complicate the code without explaining it\r\n\r\n\r\nShneidermans 8 Golden rules is a good source for software development, I use it as inspiration and almost a checklist against my work. The 8 golden rules are in line with interface design , it is a source I will be using in future projects as I think these principles are key especially consistency a good interface and more people will use the software/website.\r\nOne snatch is that Shneidermans rules don\'t cover everything that is needed in Interface Design like he hasn\'t mentioned a lot about design , a good design will follow onto a good interface.  \r\n\r\n\r\nOverall I would say the sources listed above are all good sources , some are better than some after evaluating  I would say the best free source is W3 schools I genuinely cannot believe that it is free , it has nearly everything you need for software development. Probably Shneiderman\'s golden rules source was probably the one I used the less but it still is a good source .\r\n', 0x696d616765732f363738346530646136336539642e6a7067, '2025-01-13'),
(30, 'Comparing Job Roles and Skill requirements in Software Development', 'A Blog post on Job Roles and Skill requirements in Software Development ', 'Throughout our course, we are reminded to research future job opportunities for our coming post-course.\r\nI found that there are many job opportunities which I can receive from Software Development.\r\n\r\nFirstly, I will go through the typical skills required/desired to increase the chance of getting more work options. \r\n\r\nProgramming Proficiency is an important skill. It is needed to have skill/experience in programming languages, as the phrase &quot;The more the merrier&quot; suggests. The more languages you have a good understanding of, the more chance you have of being offered a job. Even if you aren&#039;t experienced in a certain section, employers may be impressed with your knowledge of the other skills, and they would be confident that you can learn as you go. \r\n\r\nProblem-solving is a good skill to have especially in Software Development as all programmers will experience bugs/errors in their code and it will annoy them and frustrate people, but people with problem-solving skills won&#039;t give up and will think to find a solution.\r\n\r\nAlgorithmic thinking is a skill which is key in hopes for a career in software development.\r\nAlgorithmic thinking involves the ability to design, analyze and implement algorithms, it is relevant to software development as algorithms are the building blocks of software. Developers use algorithms as a plan for the code. Algorithms can lead to a more structured code but a bad algorithm can waste time and maybe hinder the code.\r\n\r\nWeb development is a skill which may not be required in some software development jobs but in a lot of them, it&rsquo;s a must-have skill. Web development is related to constant creation of new and improvements of current websites.  A good understanding of HTML, CSS and JavaScript is part of this skill.\r\n\r\nDatabase Management is a skill which could be required/desired in certain jobs. Database management is utilizing and creating a professional database for data storage and retrieval processes; it is a crucial skill for the development of an application using data, failure in database results could be costly and may lead to being relieved of your duties.\r\n\r\n\r\nTesting and debugging involves ensuring the software is functional, I like to test my code along the way as it would be easier to identify errors.\r\n\r\nCommunication is also an important skill in software development especially for group projects. I am taking part in the redeveloped Leconfield Parish Council website which I am working with a few people. As a developer, I must ask and update the stakeholders and how the project is going. Collaboration and communication ensure a decent development process aligning with team goals.\r\n\r\n\r\nAn understanding of user experience is what we have learned as the course goes on and all software developers should have an understanding of it as well. Understanding UX is crucial for developing applications which are functional and enjoyable for users to interact with. Neglecting UX may result in software being difficult to use and may not be used at all due to user frustration and dissatisfaction.\r\n\r\nGitHub is a popular website/application which programmers use daily. GitHub is a control system used to track changes in source code during software development. Proficiency in GitHub is essential for maintaining a clean and organized codebase. GitHub provides a centralized platform for hosting repositories, managing issues and facilitating collaboration among team members. GitHub is a tricky thing to use as it gets very frustrating on how to merge changes and sometimes I have to do this manually.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe job description above is a Software developer - AI trainer as mentioned before you have to be proficient in a programming language a key skill required in the job market. This has quite a decent pay and is a very good option for people with a bachelor&#039;s degree. As my course goes on I should start to see a preferred/specialist programming language.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n The job is a Java developer who has some key skills I mentioned before. Communication is a key skill in this job as seen above, the job requires communication and collaboration with other testers.\r\n\r\nThe attributes for the job mention excellent communication skills, collaboration and strong problem-solving abilities all skills I listed above are required in this role.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nIn this job \r\n\r\nCollaboration again is a main skill of this and also proficiency in programming languages like Java is required. Although I haven&#039;t learnt Java they&#039;re many other jobs requiring different programming languages but a similar job role. \r\n\r\n\r\nThis proves that software development is a good route to go down and they certainly are many options. The skills mentioned above I believe are crucial to have and should be listed in my CV. \r\n', 0x696d616765732f363738363463396337303933632e706e67, '2025-01-14'),
(31, 'A History of Computer Interfaces', 'A 1000+ word post on The origins of GUI and how it forms modern day computers. \r\n\r\n', '\r\nGUI ( Graphical User Interface) is a very big part of modern-day computers. It is how we see things as people and access computers.&nbsp; Everything uses GUI in computers; without it, we would only be able to use Command Line Interfaces (CLI).\r\n&nbsp;\r\nA common example of GUI is WIMP, which stands for Window, Icon, Menu and pointing device. These are the main parts of a GUI that everyone using computers interacts with.\r\nDesktop computers are often controlled by computer mice and/or keyboards while laptops often have a pointing stick or touchpad. Smartphones and tablets have a touchscreen.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nGUI is a part of Human-computer interaction (HCI). HCI is the field that studies and designs the interaction between humans and computers it focuses on creating an enjoyable-to-use interface. HCI improves the usability and user experience of technological systems.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nThroughout the post I will show the early start to HCI and GUI and how it has developed from the 1970s to modern day technology.&nbsp; \r\n&nbsp;\r\nThe History of User Interfaces (user-interface.io)\r\n&nbsp;\r\n&nbsp;1973- Xerox Alto\r\nThe Xerox Alto was one of the first Operating systems using a graphical user interface, the first machines were introduced On 1st March 1973\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nhttps://history.user-interface.io/img/xerox-alto/mouse.png\r\nThe Alto mouse has three buttons, the mouse could interact with the computer screen hence it&rsquo;s in WIMP. Mouses are used in modern-day computing which shows the fundamentals of WIMP and GUI haven&#039;t changed a lot, as mice are still commonly used 50 Years later. Mouses are a key part of HCI as the mouse is used for humans to interact with the computer although not all devices use mice it was popular back then and still is now.\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nhttps://history.user-interface.io/img/xerox-alto/folders-and-documents.gif\r\nThe Image above shows the files and documents on the Xerox Alto which can be interacted with using a mouse this is still in use today in File Explorer.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nBefore GUI was introduced CLI was used where the user could only interact with a keyboard and text an example of this is below.\r\n\r\nThis is a simple game using CLI rather than GUI as it is just text which is the only way to interact with the game for example a mouse couldn&#039;t change anything as you won&#039;t be able to move where you put anything.\r\n&nbsp;\r\n&nbsp;\r\nXerox Star \r\nThe Xerox Star is the first commercial personal computer to include technologies that have since become standard in personal computers. What made it different to the ALTO was the window-based graphical user interface, icons, folders, and mouse\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nhttps://history.user-interface.io/img/xerox-star/mouse.png\r\nThe mouse changed to Two buttons slowly looking more like modern-day mice.\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nhttps://history.user-interface.io/img/xerox-star/desktop.png\r\nThe Xerox Star Introduced the window-based GUI which is used today by nearly every OS, Windows and MAC Use Window Based GUI&#039;S Today and the Alto was the first to introduce it again highlighting the fundaments of GUI and the first few operating systems with GUI the principals are still in use in Modern day.\r\n\r\nhttps://history.user-interface.io/img/xerox-star/icons.jpeg\r\nIcons are another factor to make it more accessible and easier for users to understand how they are using the computer again icons are still used in modern-day OS&#039;s.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nAnother development in user interfaces is the Apple Lisa a desktop computer developed by Apple. Human-computer interactions really started to develop and take shape, the fundamentals were starting to take place which we still have today.\r\nThe Apple Lisa is one of the first personal computers to present a GUI in a machine aimed at individual business users.\r\n\r\nhttps://history.user-interface.io/img/apple-lisa/desktop-with-applications.png\r\nAs seen above the Apple Lisa has a cursor, which helps the users understand how the mouse plugged in works and where it is going allowing the human to interact with the desktop, this is a principle used in modern computers it is a really successful invention. GUI has developed here as the computer has a desktop screen and can access many windows by double-clicking on the icons which provides an interaction. The Apple Lisa here has a dropdown menu for customization this itself shows how GUI is versatile and now has many options for the user to customize their view/user experience to their needs.\r\n&nbsp;\r\n&nbsp;\r\nIn 1984 The Macintosh &#039;system 1 &#039; was the first version of the Apple Macintosh operating system and the beginning of the classic Mac OS series.\r\nThe operating system introduced many features which would appear for years to come, some that still exist in the current macOS.\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nhttps://history.user-interface.io/img/system-1/desktop-with-applications.png\r\nThe desktop had applications like notepad and control panel, and the mouse is a key part in interacting with the page as here shown above the mouse can change the volume of the audio in the computer, another principle still in modern day HCI. Also, the notepad allowed keyboards to type into the desktop and the users can store the text and see this on screen another way the human and computer interact with each other another big development still in use in the modern day. Also at the top, we can see the classical Apple Mac menu bar which is a key GUI development that keeps everything you need at the top of the screen at all times a good GUI development keeps users less confused and a consistent interface encourages users to carry on and buy the computers.\r\n&nbsp;\r\n&nbsp;\r\nIn 1985 Windows 1.0 was the first major release of Microsoft Windows a family of graphical operating systems for personal computers developed by Microsoft. Windows 1.0 was the first step in their evolution of Operating systems and their rivalry with Apple.&nbsp; \r\n\r\nhttps://history.user-interface.io/img/windows-1.0/file-manager.png\r\nAs we can see this was the list for all applications for me it was a poor start as the font is quite annoying/hard to look at and there is too much going on leading to a poor user experience from a poor GUI design. Although there is colour in the operating system which Mac didn&#039;t have other than that Mac had the advantage in terms of a good GUI.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nAlthough in 1987 Windows 2.0 was released it wasn&#039;t a massive overhaul of GUI but it was an improvement in some features. For example, windows are a big feature which is used in HCI and GUI in the modern day, Windows could be maximised minimised or closed down and they could be moved to the top by the mouse, I feel this was a great feature as the users can interact with how they want their desktop to look and its good design to make the computer less clunky and more of a freedom to it.\r\n\r\nhttps://history.user-interface.io/img/windows-2.0/desktop-with-applications.png\r\n&nbsp;\r\nIn 1990 Microsoft released Windows 3.0 which features a new graphical user interface where applications are represented as clickable icons.\r\n\r\nhttps://history.user-interface.io/img/windows-3.0/desktop-with-applications.png\r\nThe icons are a great feature of GUI. This makes the users understand what applications are accessible for maybe younger less experienced users. The windows are also looked closer to what they are in the modern day. The design was such a huge improvement from its predecessors.\r\n&nbsp;\r\n&nbsp;\r\nWindows 95 also was another development in Windows OS.\r\n\r\nWindows 11 (the latest Microsoft OS) has a very similar desktop to Windows 95. As mentioned before not a lot has changed in terms of design it&#039;s just the way graphics have developed to make designs look better.&nbsp; The start menu is a good design as users can have quick access to the applications they need. Also, the taskbar at the bottom stores current applications when you click on them they pop up as mentioned before in&nbsp; Mac the menu bar is always at the top to help users know where it is rather than searching for everything.&nbsp; \r\n&nbsp;\r\n&nbsp;\r\nThe Mac OS X Snow Leopard is the seventh major release of macOS.\r\n\r\nhttps://history.user-interface.io/img/macos-x-leopard/desktop.png\r\nThe taskbar at the bottom is very clean and has many applications that the users to have control of what they can put there which is a good feature which helps the user have the freedom of their computer and feel that they have control. Similar to windows the windows have options to maximise the window minimise or close it. The colours and design just looked much better than previous versions but interactions and basic principles are similar to what it was 20 years ago.\r\n&nbsp;\r\n&nbsp;\r\nSmartphones were also a big development of computer interfaces and are a whole different way of how we interact with a computer.&nbsp; The user experience of smartphones has been shaped by advances in software, hardware and human interaction principles like Shneiderman 8 Golden rules.\r\nThe\r\n\r\nhttps://www.stuff.tv/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2021/08/wacky_moto_phones_moto_dynatac.png?resize=480\r\nBefore smartphones, we have mobile devices called the Motorola DynaTAC which was a series of cellular smartphones manufactured by Motorola from 1983 to 1994. Early mobiles used physical keys and Num pads to dial and text The lack of design and no GUI made mobiles very limited in purpose.\r\n\r\nhttps://th.bing.com/th/id/R.016a8fdb7877f4a0877939a539fe7c6e?rik=cACVjoQ8Won4sA&amp;riu=http%3a%2f%2fupload.wikimedia.org%2fwikipedia%2fcommons%2ff%2fff%2fNokia_3310_in_hand.jpg&amp;ehk=Fm9dlZ0QIdOMtYTDuEkVgpKCSnKsc3oZBz3HTFpjigQ%3d&amp;risl=&amp;pid=ImgRaw&amp;r=0\r\nThe Nokia 3310 had a monochrome display and on the first mobile, it had a GUI. It was a basic screen that showed simple alphanumeric characters. Nokia 3310 had a simple user interface showing texts, calls and a short menu option very simple features but the same principles are in modern-day smartphones.\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nhttps://www.modip.ac.uk/sites/default/files/styles/dp_full/public/images/artefacts/002887_1.jpg?itok=sLmL_e1D\r\nIn the 1990s Phones started using menu-driven interfaces navigated by physical buttons which users could scroll through with the scroll up and down button.\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nhttps://images.macrumors.com/t/8ieVxMiaaSTj5PEvbzXC0aX3Wms=/1600x/article-new/2015/06/Original-iPhone-Twitter.jpg\r\nHowever, in 2007 the release of the Apple iPhone changed everything as they was the introduction of Touchscreens rather than touching physical buttons to move around on their phone they can swipe their screen to move.\r\nApple and many other early touchscreen phones featured a prominent home button for easy navigation.\r\nThe GUI became much more interactive, especially with the new icons and intuitive layouts.\r\nThe screen became much bigger and easier for users to interact with, although features from early phones like the Nokia 3310, the interface and the way we interact with devices completely changed with the development of the touch screen.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nAs Apple IOS carried on they opted for a more flat design eliminating 3D type textures in favour of cleaner UI elements.\r\n\r\nhttps://s.yimg.com/uu/api/res/1.2/_06GPUzlj98E1FNM28wrgw--~B/aD0yNjYzO3c9Mjk1MjtzbT0xO2FwcGlkPXl0YWNoeW9u/https://media-mbst-pub-ue1.s3.amazonaws.com/creatr-uploaded-images/2020-02/6ae8db40-518f-11ea-afeb-6dd2c892bc6c\r\nAs developments in phones went on Apple and Samsung went for a rivalry throughout the years. Samsung went back to an original design even before their time to try and encourage more elder users of phones to buy them and to be honest it wasn&#039;t very successful only selling one million copies. The phone though interacted like another normal smartphone.\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nhttps://www.google.com/url?sa=i&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theguardian.com%2Ftechnology%2F2024%2Foct%2F17%2Fiphone-16-review-more-buttons-speed-apple-standard-phone-battery-life&amp;psig=AOvVaw1qDECFthsUGniKwqS6aPv7&amp;ust=1737126118833000&amp;source=images&amp;cd=vfe&amp;opi=89978449&amp;ved=0CBQQjRxqFwoTCJDBpp7B-ooDFQAAAAAdAAAAABAE\r\nThe Latest iPhone is the iPhone 16 which has a much better quality and size compared to the first iPhone and much more features. But the principles of HCI and GUI haven&#039;t changed massively from the first one, they are still icons on the home screen which is accessed by touch screen, and not much has changed there. One change though is there is no longer a home button, but this is accessible by swiping up. We still also see the bottom has 4 apps pinned at the bottom so they are easily accessible to the user another feature brought from the first phone.\r\n&nbsp;\r\n&nbsp;\r\nSo Overall we can really conclude that the key principles and fundamentals of HCI and GUI from certain Operating systems like Windows, Mac, IOS and Android that the first features haven&#039;t changed much they&#039;re still there but may be further developed and enhanced, we can say computers look much better in the modern day and people will say that&rsquo;s due to better GUI, but the principles are still there from the Xerox Alto to Windows 11 it&rsquo;s the hardware and drivers which has caused an upgrade in design, whereas better drivers unlock more room for a better GUI. But no matter when even when we get to the iPhone 25, you would be able to see some features are still there 24 generations later&hellip;\r\n&nbsp;\r\n&nbsp;\r\nHCI has had some big developments, from the first 3-button mouse in 1973 to the gaming mouse in 2025 some principles again haven&rsquo;t changed although there are many more ways we can now interact with a computer from Voice assistants, game controllers, trackpads pens etc. But you can see that the basic principles of HCI are still there, there are more options but a keyboard and mouse are still very popular.\r\n', 0x696d616765732f363738393261306230303336362e706e67, '2025-01-14');
