(32, 'Approaches to the SDLC', 'An Blog post for Project 2 Highlighting the comparison between the waterfall approach and the scrum approach', 'Firstly before we get on to talking about the Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC) we need to know that SDLC is a structured process that enables the production of high-quality, low-cost software, in the shortest production time. The end goal of the SDLC is typically to produce superior software that meets and exceeds all customer expectations and demands.\r\n \r\nThey\'re many different ways of approaches for SDLC but before I get onto those they\'re certain phases across all approaches.  \r\n \r\n 1.Requirements Gathering and Analysis (planning)\r\nThis is the foundation of the SDLC and all approaches start with planning, as it would be not wise to start creating a code without planning beforehand. In the planning stage, all developers and stakeholders (which need to be identified first)  work together to identify the project\'s purpose, objectives and requirements. Common examples of this stage are the development of user personas, documenting requirements and defining the project scope.\r\n 2. Software Design\r\nOnce requirements and goals are clear, the next phase would be to focus on creating the design of the software, which includes deciding on which technologies or devices the software can be used on, the database schema and the design of what the software is going to look like. The goal after this stage is to plan how the software will look and function before coding.\r\n 3. Coding\r\nThe Developers turn the design into a working functional code the phase includes programming, hard work, determination and collaboration (if working in a team) are key skills in this stage.\r\n 4. Testing\r\nBefore the software is ready to be released, the software is tested to ensure it meets the requirements or the user experience criteria. Mainly testing is to test for any little bugs left in the code. Testing includes unit testing, integration testing and as mentioned user acceptance testing. The goal of this stage is to deliver functional, error-free software.\r\n 5. Deployment\r\nThe tested software is to be deployed for users/stakeholders to access this phase may include configuring servers and rolling out updates.\r\n 6. Maintenance\r\nAfter deployment, the software requires ongoing maintenance to fix bugs, add features and ensure combability with evolving systems and technologies. Like releasing update patches.\r\n \r\nThose listed above are key parts to any approach as they are in all of them but 2 popular methods are the Scrum model and The Waterfall Model.\r\n \r\nThe scrum model is more of an iterative and incremental approach while the waterfall model is linear and sequential as a waterfall flows from top to bottom it\'s inflexible as you can\'t go from the bottom of the waterfall back to the top so changes are difficult once a phase is complete while in the scrum model, it is highly flexible; requirements can change mid-project. So that is a positive and con of both.\r\n \r\nIn the scrum model the phases overlap and occur within short cycles (sprints) while in the waterfall model phases are executed one at a time in strict order you can say both methods have pros or cons depending on personal preferences the Scrum model may get confusing with phases overlap and that can cause more issues, while the slower waterfall model is strict and things are organised as one task cannot be done without the one before it, which for a project where there is plenty of time before the deadline that can be a positive approach but the scrum model may be more suited to a project where not much time is left for the deadline.  \r\n \r\nThe time frames are split between the two models the scrum model is divided into short sprints (usually 2-4 weeks) while the waterfall model has the entire project planned from start to finish with fixed deadlines, as mentioned in the last paragraphs they\'re a variety of options but in professional practice, the waterfall model seems more professional and well organised.\r\n \r\nRegarding Stakeholders there is a continuous involvement of stakeholders for feedback during sprints while the waterfall model typically has them primarily involved during the initial requirements phase and final delivery, many companies may think the waterfall method is preferred as they want to leave it for the programmers to get on with it while some may argue it is good to get feedback as the project goes on which I think is a good idea as it may help with the final product being more closer to their needs.\r\n \r\nTesting occurs throughout the development cycle in the scrum model while in the waterfall model testing occurs after the coding phase is complete, I think that the scrum method is better as testing along the way will be better than getting a clump of errors/bugs near the end and the debugging would be horrible to do.\r\n \r\nDocumentation in the scrum model is more lightweight; as the focus is on working software over detailed documentation. The waterfall approach is reliant on detailed documentation at every phase, I would say the Waterfall approach here is much more professional.\r\n \r\nThe Scrum approach has self-organising teams with cross-functional roles while in the waterfall approach teams follow a hierarchical structure with predefined roles, as mentioned before I think the waterfall model is more professional but the Scrum approach is more flexible than the cross-functional roles but this can get confusing.  \r\n \r\n \r\nTypically the scrum model is used on complex evolving projects where requirements may change along the way for example developing a mobile app where features and design may change based on user feedback during the project and the project could evolve post-release with updates etc..\r\n \r\nWhile the waterfall model is for more simple, well-defined projects with fixed requirements an example would be building software for a government agency with fixed and well-documented approaches.\r\n \r\nI believe the choice between scrum and waterfall depends on the projects nature:\r\nScrum thrives in projects requiring adaptability, creativity and collaboration while waterfall excels in situations where the scope and requirements are clear from the outset, they\'re 2 very contrasting styles with both pros and cons.\r\n', , '2025-01-16');
