(34, 'An Evaluation of Media Theories Important to Software Development\r\n', 'A post on how design principles are important in software development including Gestalt principles , laws of UX , Design principles and accessibility', 'In this post I will be going through how software development goes beyond writing code - it requires a deep understanding of how users interact with digital interfaces and process information. Media theories offer valuable insights/views into how users perceive and engage with visual elements layouts and interfaces.\r\nThroughout this post we will explore 3 different media theories that software developers should gain an understanding of:\r\nLaws of UX + Gestalt Principles help shape how users visually perceive and make sense of information.\r\nDesign Principles, which provide the foundation for crafting consistent functional and aesthetically pleasing interfaces.\r\nAccessibility Principles,  which ensure that the software can be used by individuals with diverse abilities, ensuring that no user is left behind.\r\n \r\nhttps://lawsofux.com/cognitive-bias/\r\n \r\nCognitive bias was introduced by Amos Tversky and Daniel Kahneman who introduced the notion of cognitive biases in 1972 after they observed people\'s inability to reason intuitively with greater orders of magnitude.\r\nBefore we analyse cognitive bias we get to know what it is, it is defined as a systematic error of thinking or rationally in judgement that influences our perception of the world and our decision-making ability. Simplified, based on past experiences we gain different perceptions from an event. For example, if someone is biking and crashes, they will likely gain a different perspective on doing it and may stop doing it together. This is relevant to computing software as let\'s say they download an app and it loses all their files the user will have a negative perspective of it and will more than likely stop using it ever again.\r\nMental shortcuts increase our efficiency by enabling us to make quick decisions without the need to thoroughly analyse a situation but can also influence our decision-making processes and judgement without our awareness.\r\n \r\nhttps://lawsofux.com/aesthetic-usability-effect/\r\nAnother part of Gestalt principles and the laws of UX is the aesthetic-usability effect.\r\nThe aesthetic-usability effect was first studied in the field of human-computer interaction in 1995 (You can read more about this in my other blog post on HCI)\r\nOne big principle is that users automatically use the more aesthetically pleasing design although it may not be the best website for their purpose. Although it can be argued that the design is good making it aesthetically pleasing. Visually pleasing designs can mask usability problems and prevent issues from being discovered during usability testing. People go to websites for information, yet they may discard a website for design despite everything they need there. Software developers must be aware that they have to find the middle ground between design and usability, both are great but you can\'t heavily lean towards usability as design is what brings people to the website.\r\n \r\nhttps://lawsofux.com/law-of-proximity/\r\nThe law of proximity was a law developed by Gestalt are a set of principles in psychology, first proposed by Gestalt psychologists to account for the observation to account for the observation that humans naturally perceive objects as organized patterns and objects a principle known as Pragnanz. A key part of the design is that elements nearby are perceived to share similar functionality or traits. As humans, we assume that if things are grouped they have a similarity or theme with them. Proximity can help users understand and organize information faster and more efficiently.\r\nAn example of this in websites would be the BBC Sport is that similar pages are close to each other for example they would have a lot of football news close together to try and get the user to be on the website for longer.\r\n \r\nhttps://lawsofux.com/law-of-similarity/\r\nThe principles of grouping are a set of principles in psychology, first proposed by Gestalt psychologists to account for the observation that humans naturally perceive objects as organized patterns and objects.\r\nThe human eye tends to perceive similar elements in a design as a complete picture, shape or group even if those elements are separated. As humans, we think that visually similar elements will be perceived as related. Colour, shape and size, orientation and movement can signal that elements belong to the same group and likely share a common meaning or functionality. As software developers, it is recommended that in design links and navigation systems are visually differentiated from normal text elements.\r\n \r\nhttps://lawsofux.com/cognitive-load/\r\nThe final principle is cognitive load. Which is the amount of mental resources needed to understand and interact with an interface. Cognitive load theory was developed in the late 1980s by John Sweller out of a study of problem-solving and was an expansion of the information processing theories of George Miller.\r\nAs humans when the amount of information coming in exceeds the space we have available, we struggle mentally to keep up -tasks become more difficult, details are missed and we begin to feel overwhelmed.  Intrinsic cognitive load refers to the effort required by users to carry around information relevant to their goals, absorb new information and keep track of their goals. Extraneous cognitive load refers to the mental processing that takes up resources but doesn\'t help users understand the content of an interface. It\'s key for software developers to have a design which isn\'t too overwhelming for the user, each part of the design must be useful for the user, and an annoying interface would be a reason for users to not use the website/software.\r\n \r\n \r\nDesign Principles are fundamental pieces of advice for you to make easy-to-use pleasurable designs; they represent the accumulated wisdom of researchers and practitioners in design and related fields.\r\nIn UX minimizing users\' cognitive loads and decision-making time is vital.\r\nDesigners use principles such as visibility, findability and learnability to address basic human behaviours.  \r\nNielsens \"Usability King\" identified \"ten commandments\" /key rules in design. (Read other posts for his 5 components of usability).\r\n \r\n	• Keeping users informed of system status with constant feedback\r\n	• Setting information in a logical order\r\n	• Ensure users can easily undo/redo actions.\r\n	• Maintain consistent standards\r\n	• Preventing errors or warning the user before they commit actions\r\n	• Don\'t make users remember information. \r\n	• Make systems flexible\r\n	• Design with aesthetics and minimalism in mind so the interface isn\'t cluttered with unnecessary items\r\n	• Provide plain language error messages\r\n	• Offer easy-to-search troubleshooting resources. \r\nEmpathy expert Whitney Hees also added to this:\r\n	• Don’t interrupt or give users obstacles which can frustrate the users making them seek alternative software.\r\n	• Reduce distractions \r\n	• Group related objects together ( Gestalts principle)\r\n	• Provide context\r\n	• Make designs efficiency\r\n	• Make things easy to find\r\n	• Don’t delay users\r\n	• Be consistent with navigational mechanisms \r\nAll of the above bullet points make sense and are a good help to software developers as we want users to use software with satisfaction and a good feeling, if we make users frustrated by using the software then maybe you need to address these principles.\r\n \r\n \r\nhttps://www.w3.org/WAI/fundamentals/accessibility-principles/\r\nFor the final part of the Evaluation of Media theories important to software development Accessibility principles are a must. First of all, we have to define accessibility in this context; it refers to the practice of designing software in a way that it can be used by all people with a wide range of disabilities, accessibility ensures that all users can interact with and benefit from the technology.\r\n \r\nPOUR is a very popular acronym website and the software needs to be Perceivable, Operable, understandable and robust. Before we can get on to going in-depth into what these mean and why they\'re relevant we need to know the rules regarding accessibility which are the \" Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) which are technical standards that define 10 to 13 guidelines. It was established to help content authors and developers create web content whether a website, web application or other digital technology.\r\n \r\nWeb accessibility standards rely on several components that work together this includes\r\nWeb content: refers to any part of the website including text, image forms and multimedia.\r\nUser Agents: software that people use to access web content for example desktop web browsers ( Google or Microsoft Edge.\r\nAuthoring Tools: software or services that people use to produce web content a common example would be Visual Studio Code.\r\nThese components inter-relate and support each other. For instance, web content needs to include text alternatives for images.\r\n \r\nNow onto POUR:\r\nPerceivable - We see what is going on around us with our five senses. Even when you use electronics you use some of your five senses such as touch and sight.\r\nAn example would be text alternatives for non-text content like brief descriptions of non-text content such as audio and video files (in case of being deaf).   \r\nPeople who can\'t hear audio or see video need alternatives. Examples include:\r\n	• Test transcription and captions for audio content.\r\n	• Audio descriptions, which are narrations to describe important to describe important visual details in a video.\r\n	• Sign language interpretation of audio content.\r\n \r\nOperable - Functionality is available from a keyboard web browsers should provide keyboard support like shortcuts. Users have enough time to read and use the content.\r\nFunctionality that is available by mouse is also available by the keyboard\r\nContent should not cause seizures and physical reactions or at the very least give a big warning beforehand.  \r\nUsers should always have time to read and use the content, some people may need more time than others to read and use the content.  Examples of providing enough time include providing mechanisms to:\r\n	• Stop or extend time limits \r\n	• Pause, stop or hide moving content\r\n	• Postpone interruptions\r\nUsers should be able to easily navigate, find content and determine where they are.\r\nExamples like Pages having clear titles, organized headings, the purpose of a link being evident e.t.c\r\n \r\nUnderstandable- helps users understand the information presented by using simple language. Users need to be able to understand how it works and how to complete a task efficiently and this requires consistency. Content authors need to ensure that text content is readable and understandable to the broadest audience possible.\r\nThe primary language of the page should be identified, and any unusual words should be definitions provided and using clear and simple language.\r\nMany people rely on a predictable user interface for software developers we have to help design the interface for the users to not frustrate them. Navigation mechanisms that are repeated on multiple pages appear in the same place each time.\r\n \r\n \r\n \r\nRobust- Web content is compatible with different browsers, assistive technologies and other user agents examples of how this can be achieved include\r\n	• Ensuring markup can be reliably interpreted, for instance by ensuring its valid\r\n	• Providing a name, role and value for non-standard user interface components.\r\nMeeting these requirements helps maximise compatibility with current and future user agents including assistive technologies, it enables assistive technologies to process content reliably and to present or to operate it in different ways. Some examples of assistive technologies are screen readers, braille displays or voice recognition software.\r\n \r\n \r\n \r\nSo how useful are these theories in software development?\r\n \r\nFirstly the laws of UX and Gestalt principles are interesting and should be studied for software developers. This is because it talks about users\' psychology and how the brain uses computers and tells us what we should do, as mentioned before we humans assume two pages next to each other have a similar topic. Appeasing the user and not frustrating them encourages them to use and recommend the software so overall it\'s very interesting to read into and implement some ideas into programs.\r\n \r\nI think Design principles are very important to study for software developers and would say is the best theory for improving your software, due to its help on how to make a \'pleasurable\' design I think it\'s very good for software developers to be aware around and maybe use them as a checklist and the more you consider them in your work the more professional your software is. When the \"usability king\" offers tips on how to make a design developers should take note. I think ignoring them or even doing the opposite of their advice will hinder the work you produce.\r\n \r\nAccessibility principles are a must-awareness for software developers. Especially for website developers, if you want a professional website to be used by many it has to apply to the Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG). All interfaces should have accessibility options as humans are not all the same and think the same, you simply can\'t hope everyone is pleased by your website, it has to be flexible and accessibility is a must as it will hinder the number of users in your websites, every professional software, websites, games etc. has accessibility options so for me it’s a must to be aware.\r\n', '', '2025-01-16'),
(35, 'Nielsen\'s 5 components of Usability', 'A post on Nielsen\'s 5 components of usability ', 'Nielsen\'s 5 components of Usability\r\nhttps://www.nngroup.com/articles/usability-101-introduction-to-usability/\r\nNielsen believes there are 5 main components to usability\r\n \r\nSo first of all we need to know what usability is:\r\nUsability is a quality attribute that assesses how easy user interfaces are to use.\r\n \r\nUsability is defined by 5 quality components which are key in User experience design :\r\n \r\nLearnability,\r\nEfficiency,\r\nMemorability,\r\nErrors,\r\nSatisfaction,\r\n \r\nThere are many other important quality attributes, like utility which refers to the design functionality.\r\n \r\nJakob Nielsen \"King of usability\" is an influential figure in usability and user experience design his work has laid the foundation for understanding how users interact with systems his work/principles are still researched and used today.\r\n \r\nUsability is so important in web design /User Experience design. If a website is difficult to use people will leave and seek alternatives, to try and get more people to use your website, it simply has to be useable. The framework listed above will improve the usability in this post I will go in-depth into how these components are significant and influence UX.\r\n \r\n \r\nHis first Component is Learnability which is the easiness for users to learn and accomplish tasks when they interact with the software. This is important as the users are only going to use software which is easy to understand the interface, and if it\'s hard to understand many users may delete the software or not go on it again. An example could be the start menu on Windows 11 where they can access apps and search for them.\r\n \r\nHis second component is efficiency which is how quickly the users can perform tasks once they’ve learned the interface of the software. Time is of the essence for users, they don’t want to be searching for 2 minutes where to change the appearance settings they need to have quick access to everything they need, without that they\'re likely to use alternative software. For example, Keyboard shortcuts in words like CTRL +C and CTRL + V improve efficiency.\r\n \r\n \r\nHis third component is Memorability which in this case is how easily users can return to the software and know how to work the software, this is crucial to ensure casual or infrequent users still know how to access the software and use it without learning again or watching a tutorial. For example, consistent positions are good like the menu bar on the Mac OS or the text editing at the top of Word, this principle also links to Shneiderman\'s 8 principles as he believed consistency is a key part of interface design.\r\n \r\nAnother component to the 5 components of usability is Errors which are the number of errors users make, the severity of errors and how easily they can function. It\'s crucial to minimise errors as they can get users very frustrated and these errors should be easily fixable another link to Shneiderman principles is that the software should be helping the user fix the issue, it must communicate to the user. An example of easy fixes in software for errors is in Microsoft OneNote; the shortcut CTRL + Z can undo anything from the session which can fix the error.\r\n \r\nThe final component is Satisfaction which is how enjoyable the software is for the users to use. It matters as it ensures the user has a positive enjoyable experience and they may give positive feedback online or verbally to encourage more people to use it. One satisfying component in Teams is the animation of submitting an assignment there is an enjoyable and satisfying feeling when the animation appears.\r\n \r\nThese components are all relevant today as they\'re so much software to choose from all these components have to be ticked off for it to become popular well well-known software.\r\n \r\nHow can you improve Usability?\r\n \r\nThe most basic and useful method for this is user testing where you get hold of some representative users like customers and ask the users to perform representee tasks with the design. Observe what the users do how and where they succeed and the difficulties they have with the interface, let them have full control and record what they do so it\'s easier to think about the 5 components.\r\n \r\nUsability plays a big part on role in each stage of the design process so before starting a new design test the old design to identify the good parts that you should keep and make note of the bad parts that give the users trouble. Researching into rivals/alternative software to see what they do good and bad, and make sure to focus on those bad parts and make them good in the design, this makes it more likely that people will start to use your software.\r\n', , '2025-01-18');

